# The Basket of Goods
- The basket of goods is **updated over time** to reflect trends in demand. Items are removed and added each year, but not instantly when a product becomes more or less popular.
	- The price of this basket is compared over time to calculate the rate of inflation.
	- Weighting: goods are weighted differently, to represent the impact that they have upon average prices.
		- If the price of milk increased, then this would have a more significant impact than dinner plates.
- Infrequent reweighing saves costs for the national statistical office, but delays the introduction into the index of new types of expenditure. For example, subscriptions for internet service entered the index compilation with a considerable time lag in some countries
